outputs:
{"answer": "According to the context, in the Model Context Protocol (MCP) architecture, the Client plays a key role as "The Messenger". The MCP Client is responsible for making requests and acts as a communicator. It's also referred to as the "Host" or the device that initiates communication with other components.

In more detail, the Client communicates with the Server (which hosts the data) through the Host (also known as the Local Source), which serves as an intermediary between the Client and Server. This setup enables secure and efficient access to data stored in various systems, including databases or external APIs.

So, in summary, the MCP Client is responsible for initiating communication and making requests to access data from other components.", "context": "Model_Context_Protocol_Yusuf_Ozuysal.pdf p18 | Model_Context_Protocol_Yusuf_Ozuysal.pdf p19 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p4 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p11 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p5 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p18 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p40"}

