outputs:
{"answer": "The MCP protocol focuses on structured data exchange and limited parameter validation. It doesn't include mechanisms for runtime isolation or privilege control, so its security boundaries depend entirely on its hosting environment.

One measure that can help reduce the risks of granting a Large Language Model access to a local filesystem is to use a user-controlled, opt-in authorization model. According to the provided context, this model ensures that the AI agent can only access data or perform actions that the requesting user is currently authorized to do. This is done by executing the AI agent with the user's just-in-time privileges, not those of a pre-configured, over-privileged service account.

This approach provides a strong, auditable security boundary and prevents the AI agent from accessing data or performing actions that the user themselves is not authorized to do.", "context": "MCP_landscape_security_threats.pdf p23 | MCP_landscape_security_threats.pdf p22 | the_model_context_protocol.pdf p29"}

